      },
      {
        "block_label": "paragraph_title",
        "block_content": "5.4. MIA with the Stable Diffusion Model",
        "block_bbox": [
          87,
          287,
          473,
          316
        ],
        "block_id": 3,
        "block_order": 3,
        "group_id": 3,
        "global_block_id": 111,
        "global_group_id": 111,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            87.0,
            287.0
          ],
          [
            473.0,
            287.0
          ],
          [
            473.0,
            316.0
          ],
          [
            87.0,
            316.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "We conduct experiments on the original Stable Diffusion model, i.e., stable-diffusion-v1-4 provided by Huggingface, without further fine-tuning or modifications. We follow the experiment setup of (Duan et al., 2023; Kong et al., 2023), use the LAION-5B dataset (Schuhmann et al., 2022) as member and COCO2017-val (Lin et al., 2014) as non-member. We randomly select 2500 images in each dataset. We test two scenarios: Knowing the ground truth text, which we denote as Laion5; Not knowing the ground truth text and generating text through BLIP (Li et al., 2022), which we denote as Laion5 with BLIP.",
        "block_bbox": [
          85,
          318,
          597,
          607
        ],
        "block_id": 4,
        "block_order": 4,
        "group_id": 4,
        "global_block_id": 112,
        "global_group_id": 112,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            85.0,
            318.0
          ],
          [
            597.0,
            318.0
          ],
          [
            597.0,
            607.0
          ],
          [
            85.0,
            607.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "For the difference function  $ D(x, \\hat{x}) $, since the images in these datasets better correlate with human visual perception, we directly use the SSIM metric (Wang et al., 2004) to measure the differences between two images. The results, presented in Table 3, demonstrate that our methods achieve high accuracy in this setup, outperforming baseline algorithms by approximately 10%. Notably, our methods do not require access to U-Net.",
        "block_bbox": [
          84,
          616,
          594,
          830
        ],
        "block_id": 5,
        "block_order": 5,
        "group_id": 5,
        "global_block_id": 113,
        "global_group_id": 113,
        "block_polygon_points": [
